         <div type="edition"><!-- transcription goes here -->
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>Non splendor, non diviti<hi rend="ligature">ae</hi>,
                <lb n="2"/>sed animi corporisque
                <lb n="3"/>hic datur tranquillitas.
            </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>Neither glory nor riches but peace of mind and body is given here.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary"><!-- notes go here -->
            <p>The contents are unlike any others recorded in genuine Christian inscriptions from imperial Rome, and the style of carving is unusual and suspiciously archaizing. What puts the modernity of the inscription beyond doubt is the discovery of its text written in draft in charcoal on the reverse of a similarly fabricated inscription sold by the same dealer to a buyer, Francesco Vitali di Fermo, for a private collection now housed in the house-museum of the antiquarian Ivan Bruschi in Arezzo, which has been open to the public since 2002.</p>
            <p>Recognition of the forgery and identification of the connection between the two inscriptions is owed to C. Slavich and A. Raggi, 'La collezione epigrafica dei Conti Vitali di Fermo presso la Casa Museo Ivan Bruschi di Arezzo: unâ€™indagine preliminare,' in F. Paolucci, ed., Epigrafia tra erudizione antiquaria e scienza storica. Ad honorem Detlef Heikamp (Florence 2019) 211-232 at 224-227. See also C. Slavich, La collezione epigrafica della Casa Museo Dell'Antiquariato Ivan Bruschi di Arezzo (Rome 2019) 26-29, 77 no. 83* and fig. 89b.</p>
         </div>
